{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Aguilar v. Felton |ArgueDate=December 5 |ArgueYear=1984 |DecideDate=July 1 |DecideYear=1985 |FullName=Aguilar, et al. v. Felton, et al. |USVol=473 |USPage=402 |ParallelCitations=105 S. Ct. 3232; 87 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 290; 1985 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 117 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding=Title I of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965 remedial services could not be provided on the premises of a parochial school because doing so violated the First Amendment's Establishment Clause. |SCOTUS=1981-1986 |Majority=Brennan |JoinMajority=Marshall, Blackmun, Powell, Stevens |Dissent=Burger |Dissent2=White |Dissent3=Rehnquist |Dissent4=O'Connor |JoinDissent4=Rehnquist |LawsApplied=[[First Amendment of the United States Constitution#Establishment Clause|U.S. Const. amend. I]] |Overruled=''[[Agostini v. Felton]]'' (1997) }} '''''Aguilar v. Felton''''', 473 U.S. 402 (1985), was a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case holding that [[New York City]]'s program that sent [[Public school (government funded)|public school]] teachers into [[parochial school]]s to provide remedial education to disadvantaged children pursuant to Title I of the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965]] necessitated an excessive [[separation of church and state|entanglement of church and state]] and violated the [[Establishment Clause]] of the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution]].<ref name="wilder">{{Cite book | last = Bernstein | first = Nina | authorlink = Nina Bernstein | title = The Lost Children of Wilder: The Epic Struggle to Change Foster Care | publisher = [[Vintage Books]] | year = 2001 | location = New York City | pages = 358–359 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-679-75834-1 | oclc = 48994782}}</ref>
''Aguilar v. Felton'' was subsequently overruled by ''[[Agostini v. Felton]]'', 521 U.S. 203 (1997).
