'''Christine Ballengee-Morris''' is a professor in the Arts Administration, Education and Policy Department for [[Ohio State University]]. She is the founding director of the Multicultural Center at Ohio State University. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aaep.osu.edu/people/morris.390|title=Christine Ballengee Morris|date=2011-05-03|work=Department of Arts Administration, Education and Policy|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en}}</ref>

== Biography ==
Ballengee-Morris was born on February 15, 1955. She hails from the [[Appalachia]] and claims [[Cherokee descent]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://preview.lib.ohio-state.edu/collections/rg.40.333|title=Christine Ballengee Morris Oral History Transcript and Recordings {{!}} Ohio State University Libraries|website=preview.lib.ohio-state.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref>

She grew up in the [[Dayton, Ohio]] area. After high school she attended [[Miami University of Ohio]] and in 1980 received her BS in art education. She went on to receive a MA in [[Visual arts education|Art Education]] from Miami University of Ohio and a PhD in art education from [[Penn State University]]. After graduating from Penn State in 1995 she accepted a position at Ohio State University. She now teaches classes that specialize in diversity explorations.

== Contributions ==
Ballengee-Morris has written and edited articles for the journal ''Art Education'' from at least 1998 to 2016. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ballengee- Morris|first=Christine|date=1998|title=Cultural Ecology: Arts of the Mountain Culture|url=|journal=Art Education|volume=51|pages=14-19|via=}}</ref> She also wrote a chapter in the book "Real-World Readings in Art Education: Things Your Professor Never Told You" by Dennis E. Fehr. <ref>{{Cite journal|title=Taylor & Francis Group|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/e/9781136534287/chapters/10.4324/9780203055564-15|language=en|doi=10.4324/9780203055564-15}}</ref> Ballengee-Morris' chapter, titled "Mountain Culture: No Hillbillies Here", details her view on only teaching mainstream art to students and the impact that has on their identity. <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/42022314|title=Real-world readings in art education : things your professor never told you|date=2000|publisher=Falmer Press|others=Fehr, Dennis Earl, 1952-, Fehr, Kris., Keifer-Boyd, Karen T., 1955-|isbn=9780815335412|location=New York|oclc=42022314}}</ref>

