{{Infobox Government agency | agency_name = Norwegian Directorate for Education and Training | nativename = Utdanningsdirektoratet | logo = Udir.png | logo_caption = | type = [[Etat|Government agency]] | formed = 15 June 2004 | headquarters = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] | chief1_name = [[Hege Nilssen]] | chief1_position= director | jurisdiction = [[Government of Norway]] | employees = | budget = | parent_agency = [[Norwegian Ministry of Education and Research]] | website = [http://www.udir.no www.udir.no] | footnotes = }}
The '''Norwegian Directorate for Education and Training''' ({{lang-no|Utdanningsdirektoratet}}, UDIR) is [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[etat|government agency]] under the [[Norwegian Ministry of Labour and Social Inclusion|Ministry of Education and Research]]. The Directorate is responsible for the development of [[kindergarten]], [[Primary school|primary]] and [[secondary education]] – including [[Vocational education|vocational training]]. The Norwegian Support System for Special Education (Statped) is managed by the Directorate.
The organisation, is headquarters is based in [[Oslo]] with branches in [[Hamar]], [[Molde]] and [[Tromsø]]. The Directorate was established in 2004 by then-Minister of Education [[Kristin Clemet]]. Its director from 2004 to 2015 was [[Petter Skarheim]]. [[Hege Nilssen]] is the director general (2015-.)
In 2018, the Directorate for Education was merged with the Norwegian Center for ICT in Education.
==Annulment of exam results in 2011== The results of student examinations were annulled for all 1698 test takers (in subject "''[[matematikk 1 T]]''"), because the agency had e-mailed the questions prior to the exam, as instructed by a non-authorized recipient.<ref>http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/elevavisen/artikkel.php?artid=10032380</ref>
